    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2065372372" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2065372372" />
    <a title="Cody" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4886576-cody"><img alt="Cody" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1551053892p2/4886576.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2065372372?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cody" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cody" href="/user/show/4886576-cody">Cody</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781594200090" href="/book/show/395848.Alexander_Hamilton">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4886576-cody?shelf=american-revolution">american-revolution</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2065372372" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9956994553797186138">&quot;Knowing the purity of his heart, he bore it, as it were, in his hand, exposing to every passenger its inmost recesses. This generous indiscretion subjected him to censure from misrepresentation. His speculative opinions were treated as deliberate designs and yet you all know how strenuous, how unremitting, were his efforts to establish and to preserve the Constitution.&quot; - Gouverneur Morris<br/><br/>This was a buddy read with my friend Brandice.:) <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1622474358?book_show_action=false'>https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br/><br/>Alexander Hamilton</span>
  <span id="freeText9956994553797186138" style="display:none">"Knowing the purity of his heart, he bore it, as it were, in his hand, exposing to every passenger its inmost recesses. This generous indiscretion subjected him to censure from misrepresentation. His speculative opinions were treated as deliberate designs and yet you all know how strenuous, how unremitting, were his efforts to establish and to preserve the Constitution." - Gouverneur Morris<br /><br />This was a buddy read with my friend Brandice.:) <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1622474358?book_show_action=false">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br /><br />Alexander Hamilton by Ron Chernow is nothing short of historical bibliographical perfection. Bringing to life perhaps the most misunderstood founding father, Chernow expertly chronicles the timeline of Hamilton with a keen insight, level of fairness, and all round conviction that makes this tome perhaps the single greatest source for who Hamilton really was, and it's quite an enjoyable read.<br /><br />Hamilton was born to Scottish father and English/French-Huguenot mother on the Caribbean Island of Nevis. His upbringing alone sets him aside from many of the other famous Founding Fathers, instilling him with a greater drive to succeed without the affordably and comfort many other influential American statesmen had. His rise is so fascinating, growing from a orphaned islander in the tropics to his immigration to the American colonies as a student at King's College (now Columbia University) to eventual participation in the Revolutionary War and mentorship/ father-son relationship under George Washington. Even more amazing was his participation in the Constitutional Convention, overseeing of the Federalist Papers and authorship of many of them, and his position as the first Secretary of Treasury, incurring a national debt and helping with public credit, along with other philosophical insights that laid the foundation for the United States to become the economic powerhouse that it is. Hamilton was so far ahead of his time it's hard to imagine the U.S. becoming what it is without his dedication to service.<br /><br />Of course the infamy of Hamilton and his character is addressed in this fine tome as well. The Maria Reynolds Affair, political infighting between Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, John Adams, James Monroe (along with many others), the infamous duel with Aaron Burr, his insecurity regarding this upbringing and constant need to prove himself, and the start of the political destruction of the Federalist Party are all laid bare for readers to see, and Chernow tackles each one with an appropriate amount of fairness and understanding.<br /><br />What is maybe the most significant attribute of this grand tome is the little-known details of Alexander Hamilton's conviction towards his greater ideals. The fact that he was a lifelong anti-slavery advocate and even held the controversial belief at the time that blacks were intellectually equal to whites make him more enlightened and courageous to the struggles of understanding this country faced. Further still is that he was a trustee for the Hamilton-Oneida Academy, (or Hamilton College as it is now known) a school dedicated the building of trust between whites and local Native American tribes in New York, accepting boys of both races in the hopes of laying the foundation for better understanding between the two. This is no doubt remarkable for a country whom for a long time continued to struggle with segregation and racial tension, and arguably still does. No other Founding Father could've held these beliefs as Hamilton did, particularly because of his unique upbringing that separates him from the others, who were born into "American aristocracy" and/or owned slaves.<br /><br />Hamilton is feasibly the most "American" of Founding Fathers. A poor immigrant to America who rises as an essential pillar to the country's own successes, leaving a greater footprint than most and proving his worthiness ten-fold, this victim of history finally has the recognition he deserves. Chernow's intellectual playfulness in telling his story is so good it's historical bliss.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9956994553797186138" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


